{"title_page": "Yangyang International Airport", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name         = Yangyang International Airport \n| nativename   =\n| nativename-a = \uc591\uc591\uad6d\uc81c\uacf5\ud56d<br />\u8944\u967d\u570b\u969b\u7a7a\u6e2f\n| nativename-r = Yangyang Gukje Gonghang<br />Yangyang Kukche Konghang\n| image        = File:Yangyang International Airport 20130829.jpg\n| image-width  =\n| caption      =\n| IATA         = YNY\n| ICAO         = RKNY\n| pushpin_map            = South Korea#Asia\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of airport in [[Yangyang]],[[Gangwon Province (South Korea)|Gangwon Province]],[[South Korea]]\n| pushpin_label          = '''YNY'''/RKNY\n| pushpin_label_position = right\n| type         = Public\n| hub          = [[Fly Gangwon]]\n| owner        =\n| operator     = Korea Airports Corporation\n| city-served  = Gangneung, Sokcho\n| location     = [[Yangyang County|Yangyang]], [[Gangwon-do (South Korea)|Gangwon Province]], South Korea\n| elevation-f  = 241\n| elevation-m  = 73\n| coordinates  = {{Coord|38|03|41|N|128|40|09|E|type:airport_region:KR}}\n| website      =\n| metric-elev  = yes\n| metric-rwy   = yes\n| r1-number    = 15/33\n| r1-length-f  = 8,202\n| r1-length-m  = 2,500\n| r1-surface   = Concrete\n| stat-year    = 2017\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data   = 15,780\n| stat2-header =\n| stat2-data   =\n| footnotes    = Source:airport-information.com<ref name=\"statistics\">{{cite web|title=South Korea Traffic Statistics|url=http://www.airport-information.com/website/index.php/en/south-korea-airport-traffic-statistics|publisher=airport-information.com}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Yangyang International Airport''' {{airport codes|YNY|RKNY}} is a small international airport in northeastern [[South Korea]]. It is located in [[Yangyang County]], [[Gangwon-do (South Korea)|Gangwon]] Province and was built to serve the nearby areas of [[Sokcho]], [[Gangneung]] and [[Pyeongchang County|Pyeongchang]]. The airport replaced Gangneung and Sokcho airports.\n\nIn 2011, 5,748 passengers used the airport.<ref name=\"statistics\" />\n\n[[Air Koryo]] operated charters from [[Sondok Airport]] to Yangyang Airport during 2002\u20132006 for few months per year. Flights were halted indefinitely after relations soured between the two Koreas.\n\nYangyang International Airport handled its last flight on 1 November 2008, according to the [https://web.archive.org/web/20090607090634/http://www.airport.co.kr/doc/www_eng/index.jsp Korea Airport Corporation], and there were calls for it to be sold off or closed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/8052742.stm|title=Inside South Korea's 'ghost' airport|date=18 May 2009|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> It reopened on 16 July 2010 when [[:ko:\uc774\uc2a4\ud2b8\uc544\uc2dc\uc544\uc5d0\uc5b4\ub77c\uc778|East Asia AirLine]] started flying to Busan-Gimhae.\n\nOn 4 August 2011, Taiwan's [[TransAsia Airways]] began flying to Yangyang International Airport (five times a week). TransAsia Airways stated that it will be a regular chartered service. However, on the 18th of February 2017, TransAsia Airways went into liquidation.<ref name=\"Notice of Dissolution of TransAsia Airways Corporation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tna.com.tw/NoDLetter.html|title=\u8208\u822a\u7533\u544a\u50b5\u6b0a\u516c\u544a|website=www.tna.com.tw}}</ref>\n\nWith [[Pyeongchang County|Pyeongchang]] being voted as the host city for [[2018 Winter Olympics]], Yangyang International Airport hopes to see an increase in passengers. [[Korean Air]] scheduled additional charter flights from Yangyang to Europe and North America, including [[John F. Kennedy International Airport|New York JFK]], [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul International Airport|Minneapolis St Paul]], [[Gatwick Airport|London Gatwick]], and [[Munich Airport|Munich]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/276952/korean-air-schedules-yangyang-europe-charters-in-feb-2018/|title=Korean Air schedules Yangyang \u2013 Europe charters in Feb 2018|last=2018|first=UBM (UK) Ltd.|work=Routesonline|access-date=2018-02-01|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/276895/korean-air-adds-yangyang-us-charters-in-feb-2018/|title=Korean Air adds Yangyang \u2013 US charters in Feb 2018|last=2018|first=UBM (UK) Ltd.|work=Routesonline|access-date=2018-02-01|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThis includes a visa-free grace for the Philippines, Indonesia, and Vietnam so long as citizens land in Yangyang. VietJet Air is the only airline carrier that operates flights from South East Asia to Yangyang (charter flights from Hanoi to Yangyang).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/161573/breaking-news-south-korea-visa-free-entry-yangyang-airport-visa-pyeongchang-winter-olympics|title=Visa-free entry to Korea for Filipinos, but \u2026|first=Jhoanna|last=Ballaran}}</ref>\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n'''Passenger'''\n{{Airport-dest-list\n| [[Fly Gangwon]] | [[Clark International Airport|Clark]] <ref>https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/289016/fly-gangwon-adds-clark-service-from-feb-2020/</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=Fly Gangwon moves Clark launch to late-Feb 2020 |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/289259/fly-gangwon-moves-clark-launch-to-late-feb-2020/ |website=Routesonline |accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref> [[Jeju International Airport|Jeju]],<ref>https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/287502/fly-gangwon-schedules-late-nov-2019-launch-to-jeju/</ref> [[Kaohsiung International Airport|Kaohsiung]], [[Taichung International Airport|Taichung]], [[Taoyuan International Airport|Taipei\u2013Taoyuan]]<ref>http://m.focustaiwan.tw/news/asoc/201911200022.aspx</ref>\n| [[Korea Express Air]] | [[Gimhae International Airport|Busan]] \n| [[Loong Air]] | [[Hangzhou Xiaoshan International Airport|Hangzhou]], [[Ningbo Lishe International Airport|Ningbo]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/286907/loong-air-adds-yangyang-service-in-w19/|title=Loong Air adds Yangyang service in W19|publisher=routesonline|accessdate=16 October 2019}}</ref>\n| [[VietJet Air]] | '''Charter:'''  [[Noi Bai International Airport|Hanoi]]\n| [[Yakutia Airlines]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Vladivostok International Airport|Vladivostok]]\n|}}\n\n==Ground transportation==\n\n===Bus===\n* Good Morning Tour : Yangyang Bus Terminal \u2194 Yangyang International Airport\n\n==See also==\n* [[Transport in South Korea]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.airport.co.kr/mbs/yangyangeng/ Yangyang International Airport] (in English)\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/8055957.stm South Korea's abandoned airports]\n*{{WAD|RKNY}}\n\n{{Airports in South Korea}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Gangwon Province, South Korea]]\n[[Category:Airports in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Yangyang County]]\n\n\n{{SouthKorea-airport-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name         = Yangyang International Airport \n| nativename   =\n| nativename-a = \uc591\uc591\uad6d\uc81c\uacf5\ud56d<br />\u8944\u967d\u570b\u969b\u7a7a\u6e2f\n| nativename-r = Yangyang Gukje Gonghang<br />Yangyang Kukche Konghang\n| image        = File:Yangyang International Airport 20130829.jpg\n| image-width  =\n| caption      =\n| IATA         = YNY\n| ICAO         = RKNY\n| pushpin_map            = South Korea#Asia\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of airport in [[Yangyang]],[[Gangwon Province]],[[South Korea]]\n| pushpin_label          = '''YNY'''/RKNY\n| pushpin_label_position = right\n| type         = Public\n| hub          = [[Fly Gangwon]]\n| owner        =\n| operator     = Korea Airports Corporation\n| city-served  = Gangneung, Sokcho\n| location     = [[Yangyang County|Yangyang]], [[Gangwon-do (South Korea)|Gangwon Province]], South Korea\n| elevation-f  = 241\n| elevation-m  = 73\n| coordinates  = {{Coord|38|03|41|N|128|40|09|E|type:airport_region:KR}}\n| website      =\n| metric-elev  = yes\n| metric-rwy   = yes\n| r1-number    = 15/33\n| r1-length-f  = 8,202\n| r1-length-m  = 2,500\n| r1-surface   = Concrete\n| stat-year    = 2017\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data   = 15,780\n| stat2-header =\n| stat2-data   =\n| footnotes    = Source:airport-information.com<ref name=\"statistics\">{{cite web|title=South Korea Traffic Statistics|url=http://www.airport-information.com/website/index.php/en/south-korea-airport-traffic-statistics|publisher=airport-information.com}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Yangyang International Airport''' {{airport codes|YNY|RKNY}} is a small international airport in northeastern [[South Korea]]. It is located in [[Yangyang County]], [[Gangwon-do (South Korea)|Gangwon]] Province and was built to serve the nearby areas of [[Sokcho]], [[Gangneung]] and [[Pyeongchang County|Pyeongchang]]. The airport replaced Gangneung and Sokcho airports.\n\nIn 2011, 5,748 passengers used the airport.<ref name=\"statistics\" />\n\n[[Air Koryo]] operated charters from [[Sondok Airport]] to Yangyang Airport during 2002\u20132006 for few months per year. Flights were halted indefinitely after relations soured between the two Koreas.\n\nYangyang International Airport handled its last flight on 1 November 2008, according to the [https://web.archive.org/web/20090607090634/http://www.airport.co.kr/doc/www_eng/index.jsp Korea Airport Corporation], and there were calls for it to be sold off or closed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/8052742.stm|title=Inside South Korea's 'ghost' airport|date=18 May 2009|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> It reopened on 16 July 2010 when [[:ko:\uc774\uc2a4\ud2b8\uc544\uc2dc\uc544\uc5d0\uc5b4\ub77c\uc778|East Asia AirLine]] started flying to Busan-Gimhae.\n\nOn 4 August 2011, Taiwan's [[TransAsia Airways]] began flying to Yangyang International Airport (five times a week). TransAsia Airways stated that it will be a regular chartered service. However, on the 18th of February 2017, TransAsia Airways went into liquidation.<ref name=\"Notice of Dissolution of TransAsia Airways Corporation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tna.com.tw/NoDLetter.html|title=\u8208\u822a\u7533\u544a\u50b5\u6b0a\u516c\u544a|website=www.tna.com.tw}}</ref>\n\nWith [[Pyeongchang County|Pyeongchang]] being voted as the host city for [[2018 Winter Olympics]], Yangyang International Airport hopes to see an increase in passengers. [[Korean Air]] scheduled additional charter flights from Yangyang to Europe and North America, including [[John F. Kennedy International Airport|New York JFK]], [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul International Airport|Minneapolis St Paul]], [[Gatwick Airport|London Gatwick]], and [[Munich Airport|Munich]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/276952/korean-air-schedules-yangyang-europe-charters-in-feb-2018/|title=Korean Air schedules Yangyang \u2013 Europe charters in Feb 2018|last=2018|first=UBM (UK) Ltd.|work=Routesonline|access-date=2018-02-01|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/276895/korean-air-adds-yangyang-us-charters-in-feb-2018/|title=Korean Air adds Yangyang \u2013 US charters in Feb 2018|last=2018|first=UBM (UK) Ltd.|work=Routesonline|access-date=2018-02-01|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThis includes a visa-free grace for the Philippines, Indonesia, and Vietnam so long as citizens land in Yangyang. VietJet Air is the only airline carrier that operates flights from South East Asia to Yangyang (charter flights from Hanoi to Yangyang).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/161573/breaking-news-south-korea-visa-free-entry-yangyang-airport-visa-pyeongchang-winter-olympics|title=Visa-free entry to Korea for Filipinos, but \u2026|first=Jhoanna|last=Ballaran}}</ref>\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n'''Passenger'''\n{{Airport-dest-list\n| [[Fly Gangwon]] | [[Clark International Airport|Clark]] <ref>https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/289016/fly-gangwon-adds-clark-service-from-feb-2020/</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=Fly Gangwon moves Clark launch to late-Feb 2020 |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/289259/fly-gangwon-moves-clark-launch-to-late-feb-2020/ |website=Routesonline |accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref> [[Jeju International Airport|Jeju]],<ref>https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/287502/fly-gangwon-schedules-late-nov-2019-launch-to-jeju/</ref> [[Kaohsiung International Airport|Kaohsiung]], [[Taichung International Airport|Taichung]], [[Taoyuan International Airport|Taipei\u2013Taoyuan]]<ref>http://m.focustaiwan.tw/news/asoc/201911200022.aspx</ref>\n| [[Korea Express Air]] | [[Gimhae International Airport|Busan]] \n| [[Loong Air]] | [[Hangzhou Xiaoshan International Airport|Hangzhou]], [[Ningbo Lishe International Airport|Ningbo]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/286907/loong-air-adds-yangyang-service-in-w19/|title=Loong Air adds Yangyang service in W19|publisher=routesonline|accessdate=16 October 2019}}</ref>\n| [[VietJet Air]] | '''Charter:'''  [[Noi Bai International Airport|Hanoi]]\n| [[Yakutia Airlines]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Vladivostok International Airport|Vladivostok]]\n|}}\n\n==Ground transportation==\n\n===Bus===\n* Good Morning Tour : Yangyang Bus Terminal \u2194 Yangyang International Airport\n\n==See also==\n* [[Transport in South Korea]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.airport.co.kr/mbs/yangyangeng/ Yangyang International Airport] (in English)\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/8055957.stm South Korea's abandoned airports]\n*{{WAD|RKNY}}\n\n{{Airports in South Korea}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Gangwon Province, South Korea]]\n[[Category:Airports in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Yangyang County]]\n\n\n{{SouthKorea-airport-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGangwon(link changed toGangwon Province (South Korea)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yangyang_International_Airport"}
{"title_page": "Sir Henry Oxenden, 1st Baronet", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n[[File:Sir Henry Oxenden 1st Baronet.jpg|right|thumb]]\n'''Sir Henry Oxenden, 1st Baronet''' (1614\u20131686) was an English politician who sat in the [[House of Commons of England|House of Commons]] at various times between 1645 and 1660.\n\nOxenden was the son of Sir James Oxenden and his wife Margaret Nevinson, daughter of Thomas Nevinson of Estry, Kent. He was knighted on 11 July 1660.<ref name=Betham>[[William Betham (1749\u20131839)|William Betham]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=6vzUAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA31&lpg=PA31&dq=%22Sir+James+Oxenden%22&source=bl&ots=Dkh-oVNzY3&sig=REDg5Ayw6aCviNT9mI_136Mkc2Y&hl=en&ei=tB6_TN-BKI_KjAfK2v2OAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CCEQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%22Sir%20James%20Oxenden%22&f=false ''The Baronetage of England'' Volume 3]</ref>\n\nOxenden was elected [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Winchelsea (UK Parliament constituency)|Winchelsea]] as a recruiter to the [[Long Parliament]] in 1645. He was elected MP for [[Kent (UK Parliament constituency)|Kent]] in the [[First Protectorate Parliament]] of 1654 and in the [[Second Protectorate Parliament]] in 1656.<ref name=HOP>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1660-1690/member/oxenden-henry-1614-86 History of Parliament Online - Oxenden, Henry]</ref>  In 1660 he was elected MP for [[Sandwich (UK Parliament constituency)|Sandwich]] in the [[Convention Parliament (1660)|Convention Parliament]].<ref name=HOP/>   He was created [[Oxenden Baronets|Baronet]] in on 6 May 1678.\n\nOxenden married firstly Mary Baker daughter of Robert Baker of St Martin in the Fields, by whom he had a daughter, and secondly Elizabeth Meredith daughter of Sir William Meredith of [[Leeds Abbey]], Kent. <ref>{{cite web|title=Elizabeth Meredith|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p34723.htm#i347222|publisher=The Peerage}}</ref> They had children [[Sir James Oxenden, 2nd Baronet|James]] and Henry who successively succeeded to the baronetcy and [[George Oxenden (lawyer)|George]].<ref name=Betham/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oxenden, Henry}}\n[[Category:1614 births]]\n[[Category:1686 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of England]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1640\u20131648]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1654\u20131655]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1656\u20131658]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1660]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n[[File:Sir Henry Oxenden 1st Baronet.jpg|right|thumb]]\n'''Sir Henry Oxenden, 1st Baronet''' (1614\u20131686) was an English politician who sat in the [[House of Commons of England|House of Commons]] at various times between 1645 and 1660.\n\nOxenden was the son of Sir James Oxenden and his wife Margart Nevinson, daughter of Thomas Nevinson of Estry, Kent. He was knighted on 11 July 1660.<ref name=Betham>[[William Betham (1749\u20131839)|William Betham]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=6vzUAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA31&lpg=PA31&dq=%22Sir+James+Oxenden%22&source=bl&ots=Dkh-oVNzY3&sig=REDg5Ayw6aCviNT9mI_136Mkc2Y&hl=en&ei=tB6_TN-BKI_KjAfK2v2OAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CCEQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%22Sir%20James%20Oxenden%22&f=false ''The Baronetage of England'' Volume 3]</ref>\n\nOxenden was elected [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Winchelsea (UK Parliament constituency)|Winchelsea]] as a recruiter to the [[Long Parliament]] in 1645. He was elected MP for [[Kent (UK Parliament constituency)|Kent]] in the [[First Protectorate Parliament]] of 1654 and in the [[Second Protectorate Parliament]] in 1656.<ref name=HOP>[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1660-1690/member/oxenden-henry-1614-86 History of Parliament Online - Oxenden, Henry]</ref>  In 1660 he was elected MP for [[Sandwich (UK Parliament constituency)|Sandwich]] in the [[Convention Parliament (1660)|Convention Parliament]].<ref name=HOP/>   He was created [[Oxenden Baronets|Baronet]] in on 6 May 1678.\n\nOxenden married firstly Mary Baker daughter of Robert Baker of St Martin in the Fields, by whom he had a daughter, and secondly Elizabeth Meredith daughter of Sir William Meredith of [[Leeds Abbey]], Kent. <ref>{{cite web|title=Elizabeth Meredith|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p34723.htm#i347222|publisher=The Peerage}}</ref> They had children [[Sir James Oxenden, 2nd Baronet|James]] and Henry who successively succeeded to the baronetcy and [[George Oxenden (lawyer)|George]].<ref name=Betham/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oxenden, Henry}}\n[[Category:1614 births]]\n[[Category:1686 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of England]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1640\u20131648]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1654\u20131655]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1656\u20131658]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1660]]\n", "name_user": "Uziel302", "label": "safe", "comment": "Margart->Margaret -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_Henry_Oxenden,_1st_Baronet"}
{"title_page": "Freight technology", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe '''freight technology''' sector, also known as FreightTech, refers to [[Software industry|software companies]] and technologies which assist in [[supply chain management]] and the movement of [[freight]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.freightwaves.com/news/startups/freight-tech-investment-surges|title=FreightTech investment surges in 2019|date=2019-04-16|website=FreightWaves|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref> In the five years following 2014, investment in FreightTech companies grew from $118 million to $3 billion per year.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mercercapital.com/assets/Mercer-Capital_Transportation-1Q19.pdf|title=The Rise of FreightTech|last=|first=|date=|website=MercerCapital.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.trucks.com/2019/04/29/freight-tech-vc-top-record-3-6-billion/|title=Freight Tech VC on Track to Top 2018\u2019s Record $3.6 billion|date=2019-04-29|website=Trucks.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\n== Disruption of traditional logistics and supply chain management through FreightTech ==\nThe [[shipping]] and [[logistics]] industry has long been viewed as conservative and slow-to-change,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-shipping-blockchain-maersk-ibm-idUSKBN1KU1LM|title=Maersk, IBM say 94 organizations have joined blockchain trade platform|date=2018-08-09|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-12-10|language=en}}</ref> in part due to complex relationships within [[Global shipping network|global shipping]] and [[Transport network|transportation networks]],<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.freightwaves.com/news/white-paper-the-new-economics-of-freight-brokerage|title=White Paper - The New Economics of Freight Brokerage|date=2019-08-20|website=FreightWaves|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://ecorner.stanford.edu/podcasts/ryan-petersen-flexport-modernizing-the-shipping-industry/|title=Modernizing the Shipping Industry|website=Stanford eCorner|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref> difficult documentation and customs requirements,<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/05/28/ibm-maersk-blockchain-shipping-consortium-expands-to-include-other-major-shipping-companies/|title=IBM-Maersk blockchain shipping consortium expands to include other major shipping companies|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref> lack of transparency among involved parties,<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> and obstacles to adapting quickly to sudden economic changes.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mckinsey.com/business-functions/strategy-and-corporate-finance/our-insights/the-hidden-opportunity-in-container-shipping|title=The hidden opportunity in container shipping {{!}} McKinsey|website=mckinsey.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\nRecent developments in freight technology are working to modernize and simplify [[freight transport]]. According to a report from the U.S. Department of Transportation, intelligent freight technologies have multifaceted benefits in shipping and logistics.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://ops.fhwa.dot.gov/freight/intermodal/freight_tech_story/sectionthree.htm|title=The Freight Technology Story - III. Intelligent Freight Technology Benefits - FHWA Freight Management and Operations|website=ops.fhwa.dot.gov|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref> These include increased operational flexibility and efficiency due to better planning and schedule adherence, better utilization of people and equipment, reduction of non-productive waiting times, shorter processing times, and increased shipper confidence.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nTransactional [[application programming interface]]s (API)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.re-transfreight.com/blog/what-is-api-freight-and-logistics|title=What Is an API and How Do They Streamline Freight and Logistics?|last=Charland|first=Anthony|website=re-transfreight.com|language=en-us|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref> and distributed ledger technology are expanding in the shipping and logistics sector to reduce extensive paperwork,<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.logistics.dhl/content/dam/dhl/global/core/documents/pdf/glo-core-blockchain-trend-report.pdf|title=Blockchain in Logistics|last=|first=|date=|website=Logistics.dhl|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-01}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www2.deloitte.com/content/dam/Deloitte/de/Documents/Innovation/IoT-powered-by-Blockchain-Deloitte.pdf|title=IoT powered by Blockchain: How Blockchains facilitate the application of digital twins in IoT|last=|first=|date=|website=Deloitte.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-01}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bcg.com/publications/2019/resolving-blockchain-paradox-transportation-logistics.aspx|title=Resolving the Blockchain Paradox in Transportation and Logistics|website=https://www.bcg.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref> monitor conditions and location of freight and goods in transport and make this information available to involved parties,<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/fedex-cio-looks-to-industry-collaboration-to-scale-blockchain-11556572820|title=FedEx CIO Looks to Industry Collaboration to Scale Blockchain|last=Castellanos|first=Sara|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" /> and increase transparency across the [[supply chain]].<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Truck freight ===\n{{Main|Road transport}}\n\nThe first steps to [[digitization]] in [[trucking]] came in the form of digital [[freight exchange]]s such as [[Teleroute]]<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/business/2019/05/16/uber-is-trying-to-disrupt-the-road-freight-business|title=Uber is trying to disrupt the road-freight business|date=2019-05-16|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-12-10|issn=0013-0613}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adlittle.com/en/insights/viewpoints/digital-platforms-freight-transportation|title=Digital platforms in freight transportation|date=2017-10-08|website=Arthur D Little|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref> and [[Timocom|TIMOCOM]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@janclaudio.munoz/freight-exchanges-digital-freight-forwarders-forwarding-saas-7c1229477588|title=Freight Exchanges, Digital Freight Forwarders, Forwarding SaaS|last=Munoz|first=Jan Claudio|date=2019-05-21|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bcg.com/publications/2018/to-get-smart-ports-go-digital.aspx|title=To Get Smart, Ports Go Digital|website=https://www.bcg.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":9\" />  Greater efficiency in trucking is being achieved through intelligent freight technology such as automated [[User interface|interfaces]] that can help truckers and regulatory bodies reduce stops at [[weigh station]]s and time spent at [[border checkpoint]]s.<ref name=\":5\" /> This improves schedule adherence, reduces administrative burdens, and increases fuel efficiency by minimizing time spent idling.<ref name=\":5\" /> Mobile tracking programs can also reduce theft and loss of cargo by recording instances where trailer doors are opened outside of approved areas ([[geo-fence]]s) and alerting authorities.<ref name=\":5\" /> Growing automation of quoting and booking of truckload shipments and increased automation of matching trucks with appropriate loads in a timely manner is also working to maximize efficiency for shippers and consumers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freightwaves.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/FreightRevolution_ebook.pdf|title=Technology and the Future of Freight Brokerage|last=|first=|date=|website=Freightwaves.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref>\n\nDue to the relatively short life cycle of three to four years for commercial trucks,<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.oliverwyman.com/our-expertise/insights/2017/sep/oliver-wyman-transport-and-logistics-2017/operations/disruption-the-future-of-rail-freight.html|title=Disruption: The Future Of Rail Freight|last=Wyman|first=Oliver|website=oliverwyman.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref> implementation of new interfaces and freight technologies has progressed more quickly in trucking than in other sectors.<ref name=\":11\" /> Compared with other modes of transport such as aviation and rail, however, driverless technologies for road transport have lagged behind due to road environments being more complex than separated spaces for rail and air transport.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/781295/automation_in_freight.pdf|title=New Technology and Automation in Freight Transport and Handling Systems|last=|first=|date=|website=gov.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Air freight ===\n{{Main|Air cargo}}\n\nFreight technology in [[air cargo]] is already critically important in [[Cold chain|cold chain management]] for sensitive goods such as agricultural products, vaccines, and medications.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baxter|first=Glenn|last2=Kourousis|first2=Kyriakos|date=2015-04-22|title=Temperature Controlled Aircraft Unit Load Devices: The Technological Response to Growing Global Air Cargo Cool Chain Requirements|url=https://www.jotmi.org/index.php/GT/article/view/1452|journal=Journal of Technology Management & Innovation|language=en|volume=10|issue=1|pages=157\u2013172|doi=10.4067/S0718-27242015000100012|issn=0718-2724}}</ref> Monitoring in the form of [[data logger]]s can record temperature, light, humidity, and GPS location to show whether goods have been improperly cooled, handled, or tampered with.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aircargonews.net/airlines/ccn-and-microsoft-launch-air-cargo-blockchain-first/|title=CCN and Microsoft launch air cargo blockchain first|date=2019-03-15|website=Air Cargo News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibm.com/downloads/cas/K9LX9RGQ|title=Blockchain in air cargo: digital disruption in the supply chain|last=|first=|date=|website=IBM.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref> It is estimated that billions of dollars in revenue are lost by cargo companies annually due to [[dispute resolution]] for shipment delays and lost and damaged goods.<ref name=\":14\" />\n\nThe world\u2019s first blockchain-based system for streamlining air cargo [[Cost accounting|costing]], [[Electronic billing|billing]], and [[Reconciliation (accounting)|reconciliation]] was announced at the 2019 IATA World Cargo Symposium.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aircargoweek.com/iata-wcs-2019-blockchain-comes-to-air-cargo-billing/|title=IATA WCS 2019: Blockchain comes to air cargo billing|last=Muir|first=James|date=2019-03-13|website=AIR CARGO WEEK|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Rail freight ===\n{{Main|Rail freight transport}}\n\nThe Freight Technology Group, responsible for identifying relevant technologies for the freight sector in the UK, has identified three key technical innovations already in use in [[Rail freight transport|rail freight]].<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/552492/rail-freight-strategy.pdf|title=Rail Freight Strategy|last=|first=|date=|website=gov.uk.dft|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref> These include [[timetable]] advisory systems which allow drivers to track train progress against timetables via software hosted on tablets, freight collaborative decision-making systems which offer real-time information on arrivals of freight services, and mobile consisting applications which reduce the amount of information sent manually to relevant parties and authorities by collecting information and transmitting it directly.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\nHowever, advancements in rail freight technology have progressed more slowly than in other sectors due to the decades-long life cycles of [[locomotive]]s and [[Railroad car|railcars]]<ref name=\":11\" /> and the lack of power supply in [[Goods wagon|freight cars]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bosch-presse.de/pressportal/de/en/connected-freight-trains-are-better-freight-trains-43171.html|title=Connected freight trains are better freight trains|website=Bosch Media Service|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\nA $10 billion upgrade to the [[Rail transportation in the United States|North American rail system]] was mandated by [[United States Congress|Congress]] to include automated safety overrides after a [[2008 Chatsworth train collision|2008 commuter train accident]], laying the groundwork for autonomous rails in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2019/07/29/autonomous-trains-challenges/|title=Autonomous Trains Are Ready to Roll, but May Face Challenges Gaining Acceptance|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, mining group [[Rio Tinto (corporation)|Rio Tinto]] launched the world\u2019s first autonomous heavy-haul freight railway trains in Western Australia to deliver ore from mines to ports.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.railjournal.com/in_depth/rise-machines-rio-tinto-autohaul/|title=Rise of the machines: Rio Tinto breaks new ground with AutoHaul|website=International Railway Journal|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Sea freight ===\n{{Main|Maritime transport}}\n\nThe growing number of [[smart port]]s around the world are increasing capacity and efficiency for shippers, ports, and [[Freight forwarder|freight forwarding]] partners, such as trucking carriers.<ref name=\":10\" /> Reductions in labour and machinery costs can be seen at ports thanks to improvements in automated and semi-automated [[Crane (machine)|cranes]], which reduce the need for yard transfer vehicles.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nIn\u00a02018, shipping conglomerate [[Maersk]] partnered with [[IBM]] to create TradeLens, a\u00a0platform for sharing and streamlining shipping information across shipping partners, businesses, and different authorities.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> By 2019, the platform covered nearly half of the world\u2019s shipments of cargo containers.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/big-ocean-cargo-carriers-join-blockchain-initiative-11559044800|title=Big Ocean Cargo Carriers Join Blockchain Initiative|last=Paris|first=Costas|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ibm/2019/12/09/ibm-tech-trends-to-watch-in-2020--and-beyond/#6c6383c54c1c|title=IBM Tech Trends To Watch In 2020 \u2026 And Beyond|last=|first=|date=2019-12-09|website=|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Intermodal freight ===\n{{Main|Intermodal freight transport}}\n\nFreight that is shipped using multiple modes of transport is called [[Intermodal freight transport|intermodal freight]].<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.itf-oecd.org/sites/default/files/docs/efficiency-sustainabilty-multimodal-supply-chains.pdf|title=Efficiency and Sustainability in Multimodal Supply Chains|last=Rodrigue|first=Jean-Paul|date=2018-10-17|website=itf-oecd.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref> Freight technology plays a pivotal role in intermodal freight transport by streamlining communication, documentation, and dispute resolution across various industry players as cargo changes hands.<ref name=\":16\" /> Freight technology offers a way to increase transparency across industry players at each step of the supply chain. [[Smart contract]]s, for example, can use information collected by data loggers, such as temperature data on cold chain shipments, to resolve or dispute a contract depending on whether the agreed upon terms of shipping have been followed.<ref name=\":16\" />\n\n== See also ==\n===Traditional areas of FreightTech===\n* [[Freight exchange|Freight Exchanges]]\n* [[Transportation management system|Transportation Management Systems]]\n* [[Conveyancing]]\n* [[Application programming interface]]s\n\n=== Areas of growth in the FreightTech sector ===\n* [[Distributed ledger]]s\n* Advanced [[machine learning]]\n* [[Smart port]]s\n* [[Smart contract]]s\n* [[Blockchain]]\n* [[Internet of things|Internet of Things]] (IoT)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Freight transport]]\n[[Category:Shipping]]\n[[Category:Maritime transport]]\n[[Category:Supply chain management]]\n[[Category:Internet of things]]\n[[Category:[https://blog.logycode.com/digitization-of-logistics Digitization of Logistics]]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe '''freight technology''' sector, also known as FreightTech, refers to [[Software industry|software companies]] and technologies which assist in [[supply chain management]] and the movement of [[freight]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.freightwaves.com/news/startups/freight-tech-investment-surges|title=FreightTech investment surges in 2019|date=2019-04-16|website=FreightWaves|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref> In the five years following 2014, investment in FreightTech companies grew from $118 million to $3 billion per year.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mercercapital.com/assets/Mercer-Capital_Transportation-1Q19.pdf|title=The Rise of FreightTech|last=|first=|date=|website=MercerCapital.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.trucks.com/2019/04/29/freight-tech-vc-top-record-3-6-billion/|title=Freight Tech VC on Track to Top 2018\u2019s Record $3.6 billion|date=2019-04-29|website=Trucks.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\n== Disruption of traditional logistics and supply chain management through FreightTech ==\nThe [[shipping]] and [[logistics]] industry has long been viewed as conservative and slow-to-change,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-shipping-blockchain-maersk-ibm-idUSKBN1KU1LM|title=Maersk, IBM say 94 organizations have joined blockchain trade platform|date=2018-08-09|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-12-10|language=en}}</ref> in part due to complex relationships within [[Global shipping network|global shipping]] and [[Transport network|transportation networks]],<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.freightwaves.com/news/white-paper-the-new-economics-of-freight-brokerage|title=White Paper - The New Economics of Freight Brokerage|date=2019-08-20|website=FreightWaves|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://ecorner.stanford.edu/podcasts/ryan-petersen-flexport-modernizing-the-shipping-industry/|title=Modernizing the Shipping Industry|website=Stanford eCorner|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref> difficult documentation and customs requirements,<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/05/28/ibm-maersk-blockchain-shipping-consortium-expands-to-include-other-major-shipping-companies/|title=IBM-Maersk blockchain shipping consortium expands to include other major shipping companies|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref> lack of transparency among involved parties,<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> and obstacles to adapting quickly to sudden economic changes.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mckinsey.com/business-functions/strategy-and-corporate-finance/our-insights/the-hidden-opportunity-in-container-shipping|title=The hidden opportunity in container shipping {{!}} McKinsey|website=mckinsey.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\nRecent developments in freight technology are working to modernize and simplify [[freight transport]]. According to a report from the U.S. Department of Transportation, intelligent freight technologies have multifaceted benefits in shipping and logistics.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://ops.fhwa.dot.gov/freight/intermodal/freight_tech_story/sectionthree.htm|title=The Freight Technology Story - III. Intelligent Freight Technology Benefits - FHWA Freight Management and Operations|website=ops.fhwa.dot.gov|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref> These include increased operational flexibility and efficiency due to better planning and schedule adherence, better utilization of people and equipment, reduction of non-productive waiting times, shorter processing times, and increased shipper confidence.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nTransactional [[application programming interface]]s (API)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.re-transfreight.com/blog/what-is-api-freight-and-logistics|title=What Is an API and How Do They Streamline Freight and Logistics?|last=Charland|first=Anthony|website=re-transfreight.com|language=en-us|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref> and distributed ledger technology are expanding in the shipping and logistics sector to reduce extensive paperwork,<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.logistics.dhl/content/dam/dhl/global/core/documents/pdf/glo-core-blockchain-trend-report.pdf|title=Blockchain in Logistics|last=|first=|date=|website=Logistics.dhl|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-01}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www2.deloitte.com/content/dam/Deloitte/de/Documents/Innovation/IoT-powered-by-Blockchain-Deloitte.pdf|title=IoT powered by Blockchain: How Blockchains facilitate the application of digital twins in IoT|last=|first=|date=|website=Deloitte.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-01}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bcg.com/publications/2019/resolving-blockchain-paradox-transportation-logistics.aspx|title=Resolving the Blockchain Paradox in Transportation and Logistics|website=https://www.bcg.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref> monitor conditions and location of freight and goods in transport and make this information available to involved parties,<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/fedex-cio-looks-to-industry-collaboration-to-scale-blockchain-11556572820|title=FedEx CIO Looks to Industry Collaboration to Scale Blockchain|last=Castellanos|first=Sara|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" /> and increase transparency across the [[supply chain]].<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Truck freight ===\n{{Main|Road transport}}\n\nThe first steps to [[digitization]] in [[trucking]] came in the form of digital [[freight exchange]]s such as [[Teleroute]]<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/business/2019/05/16/uber-is-trying-to-disrupt-the-road-freight-business|title=Uber is trying to disrupt the road-freight business|date=2019-05-16|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-12-10|issn=0013-0613}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adlittle.com/en/insights/viewpoints/digital-platforms-freight-transportation|title=Digital platforms in freight transportation|date=2017-10-08|website=Arthur D Little|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref> and [[Timocom|TIMOCOM]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@janclaudio.munoz/freight-exchanges-digital-freight-forwarders-forwarding-saas-7c1229477588|title=Freight Exchanges, Digital Freight Forwarders, Forwarding SaaS|last=Munoz|first=Jan Claudio|date=2019-05-21|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bcg.com/publications/2018/to-get-smart-ports-go-digital.aspx|title=To Get Smart, Ports Go Digital|website=https://www.bcg.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":9\" />  Greater efficiency in trucking is being achieved through intelligent freight technology such as automated [[User interface|interfaces]] that can help truckers and regulatory bodies reduce stops at [[weigh station]]s and time spent at [[border checkpoint]]s.<ref name=\":5\" /> This improves schedule adherence, reduces administrative burdens, and increases fuel efficiency by minimizing time spent idling.<ref name=\":5\" /> Mobile tracking programs can also reduce theft and loss of cargo by recording instances where trailer doors are opened outside of approved areas ([[geo-fence]]s) and alerting authorities.<ref name=\":5\" /> Growing automation of quoting and booking of truckload shipments and increased automation of matching trucks with appropriate loads in a timely manner is also working to maximize efficiency for shippers and consumers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freightwaves.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/FreightRevolution_ebook.pdf|title=Technology and the Future of Freight Brokerage|last=|first=|date=|website=Freightwaves.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref>\n\nDue to the relatively short life cycle of three to four years for commercial trucks,<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.oliverwyman.com/our-expertise/insights/2017/sep/oliver-wyman-transport-and-logistics-2017/operations/disruption-the-future-of-rail-freight.html|title=Disruption: The Future Of Rail Freight|last=Wyman|first=Oliver|website=oliverwyman.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref> implementation of new interfaces and freight technologies has progressed more quickly in trucking than in other sectors.<ref name=\":11\" /> Compared with other modes of transport such as aviation and rail, however, driverless technologies for road transport have lagged behind due to road environments being more complex than separated spaces for rail and air transport.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/781295/automation_in_freight.pdf|title=New Technology and Automation in Freight Transport and Handling Systems|last=|first=|date=|website=gov.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Air freight ===\n{{Main|Air cargo}}\n\nFreight technology in [[air cargo]] is already critically important in [[Cold chain|cold chain management]] for sensitive goods such as agricultural products, vaccines, and medications.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baxter|first=Glenn|last2=Kourousis|first2=Kyriakos|date=2015-04-22|title=Temperature Controlled Aircraft Unit Load Devices: The Technological Response to Growing Global Air Cargo Cool Chain Requirements|url=https://www.jotmi.org/index.php/GT/article/view/1452|journal=Journal of Technology Management & Innovation|language=en|volume=10|issue=1|pages=157\u2013172|doi=10.4067/S0718-27242015000100012|issn=0718-2724}}</ref> Monitoring in the form of [[data logger]]s can record temperature, light, humidity, and GPS location to show whether goods have been improperly cooled, handled, or tampered with.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aircargonews.net/airlines/ccn-and-microsoft-launch-air-cargo-blockchain-first/|title=CCN and Microsoft launch air cargo blockchain first|date=2019-03-15|website=Air Cargo News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibm.com/downloads/cas/K9LX9RGQ|title=Blockchain in air cargo: digital disruption in the supply chain|last=|first=|date=|website=IBM.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref> It is estimated that billions of dollars in revenue are lost by cargo companies annually due to [[dispute resolution]] for shipment delays and lost and damaged goods.<ref name=\":14\" />\n\nThe world\u2019s first blockchain-based system for streamlining air cargo [[Cost accounting|costing]], [[Electronic billing|billing]], and [[Reconciliation (accounting)|reconciliation]] was announced at the 2019 IATA World Cargo Symposium.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aircargoweek.com/iata-wcs-2019-blockchain-comes-to-air-cargo-billing/|title=IATA WCS 2019: Blockchain comes to air cargo billing|last=Muir|first=James|date=2019-03-13|website=AIR CARGO WEEK|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Rail freight ===\n{{Main|Rail freight transport}}\n\nThe Freight Technology Group, responsible for identifying relevant technologies for the freight sector in the UK, has identified three key technical innovations already in use in [[Rail freight transport|rail freight]].<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/552492/rail-freight-strategy.pdf|title=Rail Freight Strategy|last=|first=|date=|website=gov.uk.dft|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref> These include [[timetable]] advisory systems which allow drivers to track train progress against timetables via software hosted on tablets, freight collaborative decision-making systems which offer real-time information on arrivals of freight services, and mobile consisting applications which reduce the amount of information sent manually to relevant parties and authorities by collecting information and transmitting it directly.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\nHowever, advancements in rail freight technology have progressed more slowly than in other sectors due to the decades-long life cycles of [[locomotive]]s and [[Railroad car|railcars]]<ref name=\":11\" /> and the lack of power supply in [[Goods wagon|freight cars]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bosch-presse.de/pressportal/de/en/connected-freight-trains-are-better-freight-trains-43171.html|title=Connected freight trains are better freight trains|website=Bosch Media Service|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\nA $10 billion upgrade to the [[Rail transportation in the United States|North American rail system]] was mandated by [[United States Congress|Congress]] to include automated safety overrides after a [[2008 Chatsworth train collision|2008 commuter train accident]], laying the groundwork for autonomous rails in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2019/07/29/autonomous-trains-challenges/|title=Autonomous Trains Are Ready to Roll, but May Face Challenges Gaining Acceptance|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, mining group [[Rio Tinto (corporation)|Rio Tinto]] launched the world\u2019s first autonomous heavy-haul freight railway trains in Western Australia to deliver ore from mines to ports.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.railjournal.com/in_depth/rise-machines-rio-tinto-autohaul/|title=Rise of the machines: Rio Tinto breaks new ground with AutoHaul|website=International Railway Journal|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Sea freight ===\n{{Main|Maritime transport}}\n\nThe growing number of [[smart port]]s around the world are increasing capacity and efficiency for shippers, ports, and [[Freight forwarder|freight forwarding]] partners, such as trucking carriers.<ref name=\":10\" /> Reductions in labour and machinery costs can be seen at ports thanks to improvements in automated and semi-automated [[Crane (machine)|cranes]], which reduce the need for yard transfer vehicles.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nIn\u00a02018, shipping conglomerate [[Maersk]] partnered with [[IBM]] to create TradeLens, a\u00a0platform for sharing and streamlining shipping information across shipping partners, businesses, and different authorities.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> By 2019, the platform covered nearly half of the world\u2019s shipments of cargo containers.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/big-ocean-cargo-carriers-join-blockchain-initiative-11559044800|title=Big Ocean Cargo Carriers Join Blockchain Initiative|last=Paris|first=Costas|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ibm/2019/12/09/ibm-tech-trends-to-watch-in-2020--and-beyond/#6c6383c54c1c|title=IBM Tech Trends To Watch In 2020 \u2026 And Beyond|last=|first=|date=2019-12-09|website=|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Intermodal freight ===\n{{Main|Intermodal freight transport}}\n\nFreight that is shipped using multiple modes of transport is called [[Intermodal freight transport|intermodal freight]].<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.itf-oecd.org/sites/default/files/docs/efficiency-sustainabilty-multimodal-supply-chains.pdf|title=Efficiency and Sustainability in Multimodal Supply Chains|last=Rodrigue|first=Jean-Paul|date=2018-10-17|website=itf-oecd.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref> Freight technology plays a pivotal role in intermodal freight transport by streamlining communication, documentation, and dispute resolution across various industry players as cargo changes hands.<ref name=\":16\" /> Freight technology offers a way to increase transparency across industry players at each step of the supply chain. [[Smart contract]]s, for example, can use information collected by data loggers, such as temperature data on cold chain shipments, to resolve or dispute a contract depending on whether the agreed upon terms of shipping have been followed.<ref name=\":16\" />\n\n== See also ==\n===Traditional areas of FreightTech===\n* [[Freight exchange|Freight Exchanges]]\n* [[Transportation management system|Transportation Management Systems]]\n* [[Conveyancing]]\n* [[Application programming interface]]s\n\n=== Areas of growth in the FreightTech sector ===\n* [[Distributed ledger]]s\n* Advanced [[machine learning]]\n* [[Smart port]]s\n* [[Smart contract]]s\n* [[Blockchain]]\n* [[Internet of things|Internet of Things]] (IoT)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Freight transport]]\n[[Category:Shipping]]\n[[Category:Maritime transport]]\n[[Category:Supply chain management]]\n[[Category:Internet of things]]\n[[Category:Logistics]]\n", "name_user": "NegiGaurav", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eReferences)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freight_technology"}
{"title_page": "Miners' International Federation", "text_new": "{{Infobox Union\n|name= Miners' International Federation\n|country= International\n|affiliation=[[International Confederation of Free Trade Unions|ICFTU]]\n|members= 4.2 million (1994)\n|full_name= \n|native_name=\n|image= Miners' International Federation.jpg\n|founded= 1890\n|head=\n|dissolved_date= 1995\n|dissolved_state= Merged into\n|merged_into= [[International Federation of Chemical, Energy, Mine and General Workers' Unions]]\n|office= [[Russell Square]], London (1890&ndash;1984)<br/>Belgium (1985&ndash;1995)\n|people= \n|website= \n|footnotes= \n}}\n\nThe '''Miners' International Federation''' (MIF), sometimes known as the '''International Federation of Miners''', was a [[global union federation]] of [[trade union]]s.\n\n==History==\nThe federation was established in 1890 at a meeting in [[Brussels]] by unions from [[Austria]], [[Belgium]], [[France]], [[Germany]] and the [[United Kingdom]].  It was initially one of the largest union federations, with membership reaching 1.2 million in 1913, and this grew slightly to  1.5 million in 1931.<ref name=\"docherty\">James C. Docherty and Sjaak van der Velden, ''Historical Dictionary of Organized Labor'', pp.183</ref>\n\nFrom the 1950s, the MIF began to campaign for common international minimum working conditions.  However, with reductions in the number of miners in its heartland of Western Europe, its overall membership began to fall, and was below one million by 1976. <ref name=\"docherty\" /> \n\nThe union was based in [[London]] for many years, with the British [[National Union of Mineworkers (UK)|National Union of Mineworkers]] (NUM) as its largest affiliate.  In 1983, [[Arthur Scargill]], leader of the NUM, proposed dissolving the federation and forming a new one with the [[World Federation of Trade Unions]]-affiliated [[Trade Unions International of Miners]].  This was opposed by a majority of members, but the NUM nevertheless withdrew, leaving the federation to relocate its headquarters to [[Brussels]] and struggle with a shortage of funds.<ref name=\"scargill\">Ronald Payne and Gary Busch, \"[http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/30th-november-1985/13/scargill-goes-international Scargill goes international]\", ''[[The Spectator]]'', 30 November 1985</ref>\n\nThe MIF began recruiting unions in other parts of the world, and by 1994 consisted of 58 unions with 4.2 million members.  In 1995, it merged with the [[International Federation of Chemical and General Workers' Unions]] to form the [[International Federation of Chemical, Energy, Mine and General Workers' Unions]].<ref name=\"docherty\" />\n\n==Affiliates==\nIn 1960, the following unions were affiliated to the federation:<ref name=\"goldberg\">{{cite book |last1=Goldberg |first1=Arthur |title=Directory of International Trade Union Organizations |date=1960 |publisher=United States Department of Labour |location=Washington DC |pages=10.1&ndash;10.16}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Union !! Country !! Affiliated membership\n|-\n| All-Japan Federation of Metal Mine Workers' Unions || Japan || 57,000\n|-\n| Associated Mineworkers of Southern Rhodesia || Southern Rhodesia || 1,000\n|-\n| Confederation of Copper Workers || Chile || 24,000\n|-\n| Cyprus Federation of Free Miners || Cyprus || 1,530\n|-\n| Federation of Miners of Greece || Greece || 30,000\n|-\n| Federation of Mine Workers || Tunisia || 6,125\n|-\n| Free Italian Federation of Workers in Mining Industries || Italy || 12,656\n|-\n| General Netherlands Miners' Union || Netherlands || 3,000\n|-\n| General Union of Spanish Workers || Spain || ''Unknown''\n|-\n| [[Ghana Mine Workers' Union]] || Ghana || 40,000\n|-\n| [[Indian National Mineworkers' Federation]] || India || 150,000\n|-\n| [[Japan Coal Miners' Union]] || Japan || 200,441\n|-\n| Korean Mine Workers' Federation || South Korea || 28,246\n|-\n| Luxembourg Workers' Federation || Luxembourg || 2,000\n|-\n| Manpower Citizens' Association || British Guiana || 2,000\n|-\n| National Coal Mine Workers' Union || Japan || 75,000\n|-\n| [[National Federation of Miners]] || France || 21,000\n|-\n| National Mines and Allied Workers' Union || Philippines || 3,000\n|-\n| National Mineworkers' Union || Italy || 14,610\n|-\n| [[National Union of Mineworkers (UK)|National Union of Mineworkers]] || United Kingdom || 675,000\n|-\n| Nigerian Mineworkers' Federation || Nigeria || 10,000\n|-\n| [[Northern Rhodesian African Mineworkers' Union]] || Northern Rhodesia || 36,000\n|-\n| [[Northern Rhodesia Mine Workers' Union]] || Northern Rhodesia || 4,500\n|-\n| Norwegian Union of General Workers || Norway || 6,000\n|-\n| Suriname Mine Workers' Union || Suriname || 80\n|-\n| Swedish Miners' Union || Sweden || 14,000\n|-\n| Tanganyika Mine Workers' Union || Tanganyika || 1,000\n|-\n| [[Union of Metal, Mining and Energy]] || Austria || 25,000\n|-\n| [[Union of Mineworkers of Belgium]] || Belgium || 36,000\n|-\n| [[United Mine Workers of America]] || United States || 600,000\n|-\n| United Mineworkers of New Zealand || New Zealand || 3,320\n|-\n| United Mineworkers of Sierra Leone || Sierra Leone || 5,500\n|-\n| [[Union of Mining and Energy]] || West Germany || 461,674\n|-\n| Union of Mining, Metallurgical and Chemical Workers of Yugoslavia || Yugoslavia || 95,000\n|}\n\n==Leadership==\n===Secretaries===\n:1890: [[Thomas Ashton (trade unionist)|Thomas Ashton]]\n:1921: [[Frank Hodges (trade unionist)|Frank Hodges]]\n:1927: [[Achille Delattre]]\n:1934: [[Ebby Edwards]]\n:1947: [[Will Lawther]]\n:1957: [[Ernest Jones (trade unionist)|Ernest Jones]]\n:1960: [[Ted Jones (trade unionist)|Ted Jones]]\n:1963: Dennis Edwards\n:1976: Peter Tait\n:1984: Jan Olyslaegers\n:1989: Peter Michalzik\n\n===Presidents===\n:1910s: [[Robert Smillie]]\n:1921: [[Herbert Smith (trade unionist)|Herbert Smith]]\n:1929: [[Joseph Dejardin]]\n:1932: Fritz Husemann\n:1934: [[Pierre Vigne (trade unionist)|Pierre Vigne]]\n:1945: [[Achille Delattre]]\n:1954: [[Heinrich Imig]]\n:1956: [[Nicolas Dethier]]\n:1963: [[Heinrich Gutermuth]]\n:1967: [[Walter Arendt]]\n:1969:\n:1971: [[Adolf Schmidt]]\n:1984: Anders Stendalen\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{ICFTU}}\n[[Category:Global union federations]]\n[[Category:Mining trade unions]]\n[[Category:Trade unions established in 1890]]\n[[Category:Trade unions disestablished in 1995]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Union\n|name= Miners' International Federation\n|country= International\n|affiliation=[[International Confederation of Free Trade Unions|ICFTU]]\n|members= 4.2 million (1994)\n|full_name= \n|native_name=\n|image= Miners' International Federation.jpg\n|founded= 1890\n|head=\n|dissolved_date= 1995\n|dissolved_state= Merged into\n|merged_into= [[International Federation of Chemical, Energy, Mine and General Workers' Unions]]\n|office= [[Russell Square]], London (1890&ndash;1984)<br/>Belgium (1985&ndash;1995)\n|people= \n|website= \n|footnotes= \n}}\n\nThe '''Miners' International Federation''' (MIF), sometimes known as the '''International Federation of Miners''', was a [[global union federation]] of [[trade union]]s.\n\n==History==\nThe federation was established in 1890 at a meeting in [[Brussels]] by unions from [[Austria]], [[Belgium]], [[France]], [[Germany]] and the [[United Kingdom]].  It was initially one of the largest union federations, with membership reaching 1.2 million in 1913, and this grew slightly to  1.5 million in 1931.<ref name=\"docherty\">James C. Docherty and Sjaak van der Velden, ''Historical Dictionary of Organized Labor'', pp.183</ref>\n\nFrom the 1950s, the MIF began to campaign for common international minimum working conditions.  However, with reductions in the number of miners in its heartland of Western Europe, its overall membership began to fall, and was below one million by 1976. <ref name=\"docherty\" /> \n\nThe union was based in [[London]] for many years, with the British [[National Union of Mineworkers (UK)|National Union of Mineworkers]] (NUM) as its largest affiliate.  In 1983, [[Arthur Scargill]], leader of the NUM, proposed dissolving the federation and forming a new one with the [[World Federation of Trade Unions]]-affiliated [[Trade Unions International of Miners]].  This was opposed by a majority of members, but the NUM nevertheless withdrew, leaving the federation to relocate its headquarters to [[Brussels]] and struggle with a shortage of funds.<ref name=\"scargill\">Ronald Payne and Gary Busch, \"[http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/30th-november-1985/13/scargill-goes-international Scargill goes international]\", ''[[The Spectator]]'', 30 November 1985</ref>\n\nThe MIF began recruiting unions in other parts of the world, and by 1994 consisted of 58 unions with 4.2 million members.  In 1995, it merged with the [[International Federation of Chemical and General Workers' Unions]] to form the [[International Federation of Chemical, Energy, Mine and General Workers' Unions]].<ref name=\"docherty\" />\n\n==Affiliates==\nIn 1960, the following unions were affiliated to the federation:<ref name=\"goldberg\">{{cite book |last1=Goldberg |first1=Arthur |title=Directory of International Trade Union Organizations |date=1960 |publisher=United States Department of Labour |location=Washington DC |pages=10.1&ndash;10.16}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Union !! Country !! Affiliated membership\n|-\n| All-Japan Federation of Metal Mine Workers' Unions || Japan || 57,000\n|-\n| Associated Mineworkers of Southern Rhodesia || Southern Rhodesia || 1,000\n|-\n| Confederation of Copper Workers || Chile || 24,000\n|-\n| Cyprus Federation of Free Miners || Cyprus || 1,530\n|-\n| Federation of Miners of Greece || Greece || 30,000\n|-\n| Federation of Mine Workers || Tunisia || 6,125\n|-\n| Free Italian Federation of Workers in Mining Industries || Italy || 12,656\n|-\n| General Netherlands Miners' Union || Netherlands || 3,000\n|-\n| General Union of Spanish Workers || Spain || ''Unknow