}} Hayden McTavish || {{flagicon|ITA}} Arash Ommati\n|-\n|2014|| {{flagicon|JPN}} Kota Yamamoto || {{flagicon|USA}} Nikolai Zielinski || {{flagicon|KOR}} [[Park Se-jun|Sejun Park]]\n|-\n|2015|| {{flagicon|JPN}} Kotone Yasue || {{flagicon|UK}} Mark McQuillan || {{flagicon|JPN}} Shoma Honami\n|-\n|2016|| {{flagicon|USA}} Cory Connor || {{flagicon|USA}} Carson Confer || {{flagicon|USA}} Wolfe Glick\n|-\n|2017|| {{flagicon|AUS}} Nicholas Kan || {{flagicon|KOR}} Hong Juyoung || {{flagicon|JPN}} Ryota Otsubo\n|-\n|2018|| {{flagicon|JPN}} Wonn Lee || {{flagicon|USA}} James Evans || {{flagicon|ECU}} Paul Ruiz\n|-\n|2019|| {{flagicon|TAI}} Pi Wu || {{flagicon|JPN}} Ko Tsukide || {{flagicon|JPN}} Naoto Mizobuchi\n|}\n\n===Pokk\u00e9n Tournament===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Seniors\n! Masters\n|-\n|2016|| {{flagicon|USA}} Woomy!gun || {{flagicon|JPN}} Potetin\n|-\n|2017|| N/A || {{flagicon|JPN}} Tonosuma\n|-\n|2018|| {{flagicon|JPN}} Kato || {{flagicon|USA}} ThankSwalot\n|-\n|2019|| {{flagicon|USA}} Ashgreninja1 || {{flagicon|JPN}} Subatan\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[2014 Pok\u00e9mon World Championships]]\n*[[2015 Pok\u00e9mon World Championships]]\n*[[2016 Pok\u00e9mon World Championships]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Pok\u00e9mon}}\n{{Esports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pok\u00e9mon World Championships}}\n\n[[Category:Pok\u00e9mon World Championships| ]]\n[[Category:Pok\u00e9mon competitions]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 2004]]\n", "name_user": "SmashStar30", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pok%C3%A9mon_World_Championships"}
{"title_page": "Wyberton", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country= England\n|coordinates= {{coord|52.954041|-0.041179|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name= Wyberton\n|map_alt=\n|static_image_name= St Leodegar's Church, Wyberton - geograph.org.uk - 102124.jpg\n|static_image_alt=\n|static_image_caption= St Leodegar's Church, Wyberton\n|population= 3,747\n|population_ref= ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011]])\n|shire_district= [[Borough of Boston|Boston]]\n|shire_county= [[Lincolnshire]]\n|region= East Midlands\n|constituency_westminster= [[Boston and Skegness (UK Parliament constituency)|Boston and Skegness]]\n|post_town= BOSTON\n|postcode_district= PE21\n|postcode_area= PE\n|dial_code= 01205\n|os_grid_reference= TF316414\n|london_distance_mi= 100<!-- straight line per MOS \u2013 constant and comparable with other place distances -->\n|london_direction= S\n}}\n__NOTOC__  \n'''Wyberton''' is a village in [[Lincolnshire]], England.  It lies just south-west of [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]], and on the [[B1397 road|B1397]] &ndash; the former A16 London Road &ndash; between Boston and [[Kirton, Lincolnshire|Kirton]]. The [[A16 road (England)|A16]] along the former East Lincolnshire railway line bisects the village. The population of the civil parish at the 2011 census was 3,747.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11131021&c=Wyberton&d=16&e=62&g=6445876&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1465036982984&enc=1|title=Civil Parish population 2011|accessdate=4 June 2016|publisher=Office for National Statistics|work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref>\n\nWyberton is one of eighteen [[Civil parish|parishes]] which, together with [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]], form the [[Boston (borough)|Borough of Boston]]. The local government has been arranged in this way since the reorganization of 1 April 1974, which resulted from the [[Local Government Act 1972]]. Wyberton forms an electoral ward in itself. Since the local elections in May 2011, Wyberton has 2 Boston Borough Councillors, Cllr James Knowles (Conservative) and Richard Austin (Boston District Independents)\n\nHitherto, the parish had formed part of [[Boston Rural District]], in the [[Parts of Holland]]. Holland was one of the three divisions &ndash; formally known as \"parts\" &ndash; of the traditional county of Lincolnshire. Since the [[Act of Parliament|Local Government Act]] of 1888, Holland had been in most respects a county in itself.\n\n==History==\nWyberton is listed in the 1086 ''[[Domesday Book]]'' with 36 households and a church.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wyberton|url=http://www.domesdaymap.co.uk/place/TF3141/wyberton/|work=Domesday Map|publisher=Ann Powell-Smith/University of Hull|accessdate=30 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe lost hamlet of '''Tytton''' was mentioned in 1316 and is now represented by Tytton hall, a modern farm-house, near which is the\nmoated site of the earlier mansion. Margart{{typo help inline|reason=similar to Margaret|date=April 2020}} Tytton of Wyberton married John Coppeldyke, who was [[High Sheriff of Lincolnshire|Sheriff]] of the county in 1488. The Tytton name does not appear in the Register Book of 1538, and the family had probably become extinct by that time.<ref>{{PastScape|mname=Tytton|mnumber=353959|accessdate=30 August 2011}}</ref>\nWyberton Woad mill operated by steam was owned by Mr J Short until 1901/2.<ref>{{cite book|title=Woad in the Fens|author=Norman T.Wills|publisher=N.T.Wills|year=1979}}</ref>\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[File:Wyberts Castle, site of - geograph.org.uk - 265817.jpg|thumb|left|160px|Site of Wyberts Castle]]\nThe parish church is a Grade I [[listed building]] dedicated to Saint Leodegar and dating from the late 12th century, although it was rebuilt around 1420. The [[chancel]] was rebuilt in 1760 and the church was restored by [[George Gilbert Scott Junior]] about 1880. The original church had a crossing tower which collapsed in 1419. The [[baptismal font|font]] is 15th century and there is a charity board in the north aisle dated 1794. In the north aisle there is a 14th-century black [[marble]] slab to Adam of Frampton and his wife. Records in the [[Court of Chancery|Chancery Court]] refer to proceedings between 1426 and 1432 where Roger Derrys, a London mason, was suing for payment following the rebuilding of Church [[Steeple (architecture)|tower]] and [[nave]]. The [[chancel]] rebuilding was carried out at the same time as the refronting of the Rectory, now Wyberton Park, by the Rector Dr John Shaw.<ref>{{NHLE|desc=St Leodegar|num=1147881|accessdate=30 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nWyberton Park, the tiled-roof red brick Grade II* listed former rectory {{convert|100|yd|m|sigfig=1}} to the south of the church, was built in 1689 by the incumbent, to replace a mud and stud rectory with one containing a \"kitchen, parlour, large staircase rising from the entrance door, two chambers, a large study and small closets on the second storey and garrets, and a large porch with steps ascending to it at the entrance.\" This improved rectory is seen by historian T. W. Beastall as indicating growing prosperity through increased acreage for crops and [[Animal husbandry|husbandry]] precipitated by fen drainage during the [[British Agricultural Revolution|Agricultural Revolution]].<ref name=Beastall>Beastall T.W. (1978), ''The Agricultural Revolution in Lincolnshire'', (History of Lincolnshire, volume 8), History of Lincolnshire Committee for the Society for Lincolnshire History and Archaeology, p.8. {{ISBN|0902668072}}</ref> The present house is a further 1761 part rebuild.<ref>{{NHLE|num= 1062042|desc=Wyberton Park, Church Lane, Wyberton|accessdate= 9 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nWyberts Castle is a [[scheduled monument|scheduled]] medieval moated site located at the south end of Wybert Lane, about {{convert|1|mi|km|1}} east of Wyberton. Excavations undertaken in 1959-1960 revealed remains of stone structures on the eastern half of the island, associated with pottery which suggested that the moated site was occupied during the 12th and 13th centuries and possibly until the 15th century. In the 18th century it was known as 'Wells Slade', suggesting that it was held by the Wells family who had a manor in Wyberton in the 14th century. The name 'Wybert's Castle' is thought to be of late 19th-century origin.<ref>{{NHLE|desc=Wyberts Castle|num=1018583|accessdate=30 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe village [[public house]] is the Pincushion Inn on London Road to the south of the village.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%; width:70%; border:0; text-align:center; line-height:120%;\"\n! colspan=\"12\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;\"|Population of Wyberton [[Civil Parish]]\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#9cc; color:navy; height:17px;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1801\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1811\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1821\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1831\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1841\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1851\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1881\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1891\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1901\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1911\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1921\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1931\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1951\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1961\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 2001\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 2011\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!  style=\"background:#9cc; color:navy; height:17px;\"| Population<ref>{{cite web|title=Vision of Britain|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/data_theme_page.jsp?u_id=10463907&c_id=10001043&data_theme=T_POP|accessdate=30 August 2011}}</ref>\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 477\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 353\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 487\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 530\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 584\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 647\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 646\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 659\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 627\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 653\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 664\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 829\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 1,809\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 2,889\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 3,790\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 3,747\n|}\n\n{{Geographic location\n|title = '''Destinations from Wyberton'''\n|Northwest = [[Brothertoft]], [[Langrick]], [[Coningsby]]\n|North     = [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]], [[Frithville]], [[Sibsey]]\n|Northeast = [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]], [[benington, Lincolnshire|Benington]], [[Skegness]]\n|West      = [[Kirton Holme]], [[Swineshead, Lincolnshire|Swineshead]], [[Helpringham]]\n|Centre    = Wyberton\n|East      = [[Freiston Shore]]\n|Southwest = [[Bicker, Lincolnshire|Bicker]], [[Algarkirk]], [[Spalding, Lincolnshire|Spalding]]\n|South     = [[Kirton, Lincolnshire|Kirton]], [[Fosdyke]], [[Holbeach, Lincolnshire|Holbeach]]\n|Southeast = [[Frampton, Lincolnshire|Frampton]], [[Skeldyke]]\n}}\n\n==Notable former inhabitants==<!-- This section is linked from [[London Borough of Lewisham]] -->\n*[[William Webster (builder)|William Webster]] &ndash; Builder - associated with a number of Thames embankments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icevirtuallibrary.com/doi/abs/10.1680/imotp.1888.20967|title=OBITUARY. WILLIAM WEBSTER, 1819-1888.|publisher=Institution of Civil Engineers}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Wyberton}}\n* [http://www.lincolnshire.gov.uk/windmills/section.asp?catId=3331 Former Wyberton Mill]\n* [http://www.wyberton.com Village web site (in construction)]\n* [http://www.boston.gov.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=850&Itemid=3497 Parish council]\n* [http://www.roffe.freeserve.co.uk/earthworks/moats/wyberton.htm Wybert's Castle]\n\n{{Portal bar|England|United Kingdom}}\n{{Lincolnshire|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Borough of Boston]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country= England\n|coordinates= {{coord|52.954041|-0.041179|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name= Wyberton\n|map_alt=\n|static_image_name= St Leodegar's Church, Wyberton - geograph.org.uk - 102124.jpg\n|static_image_alt=\n|static_image_caption= St Leodegar's Church, Wyberton\n|population= 3,747\n|population_ref= ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011]])\n|shire_district= [[Borough of Boston|Boston]]\n|shire_county= [[Lincolnshire]]\n|region= East Midlands\n|constituency_westminster= [[Boston and Skegness (UK Parliament constituency)|Boston and Skegness]]\n|post_town= BOSTON\n|postcode_district= PE21\n|postcode_area= PE\n|dial_code= 01205\n|os_grid_reference= TF316414\n|london_distance_mi= 100<!-- straight line per MOS \u2013 constant and comparable with other place distances -->\n|london_direction= S\n}}\n__NOTOC__  \n'''Wyberton''' is a village in [[Lincolnshire]], England.  It lies just south-west of [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]], and on the [[B1397 road|B1397]] &ndash; the former A16 London Road &ndash; between Boston and [[Kirton, Lincolnshire|Kirton]]. The [[A16 road (England)|A16]] along the former East Lincolnshire railway line bisects the village. The population of the civil parish at the 2011 census was 3,747.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11131021&c=Wyberton&d=16&e=62&g=6445876&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1465036982984&enc=1|title=Civil Parish population 2011|accessdate=4 June 2016|publisher=Office for National Statistics|work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref>\n\nWyberton is one of eighteen [[Civil parish|parishes]] which, together with [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]], form the [[Boston (borough)|Borough of Boston]]. The local government has been arranged in this way since the reorganization of 1 April 1974, which resulted from the [[Local Government Act 1972]]. Wyberton forms an electoral ward in itself. Since the local elections in May 2011, Wyberton has 2 Boston Borough Councillors, Cllr James Knowles (Conservative) and Richard Austin (Boston District Independents)\n\nHitherto, the parish had formed part of [[Boston Rural District]], in the [[Parts of Holland]]. Holland was one of the three divisions &ndash; formally known as \"parts\" &ndash; of the traditional county of Lincolnshire. Since the [[Act of Parliament|Local Government Act]] of 1888, Holland had been in most respects a county in itself.\n\n==History==\nWyberton is listed in the 1086 ''[[Domesday Book]]'' with 36 households and a church.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wyberton|url=http://www.domesdaymap.co.uk/place/TF3141/wyberton/|work=Domesday Map|publisher=Ann Powell-Smith/University of Hull|accessdate=30 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe lost hamlet of '''Tytton''' was mentioned in 1316 and is now represented by Tytton hall, a modern farm-house, near which is the\nmoated site of the earlier mansion. Margart Tytton of Wyberton married John Coppeldyke, who was [[High Sheriff of Lincolnshire|Sheriff]] of the county in 1488. The Tytton name does not appear in the Register Book of 1538, and the family had probably become extinct by that time.<ref>{{PastScape|mname=Tytton|mnumber=353959|accessdate=30 August 2011}}</ref>\nWyberton Woad mill operated by steam was owned by Mr J Short until 1901/2.<ref>{{cite book|title=Woad in the Fens|author=Norman T.Wills|publisher=N.T.Wills|year=1979}}</ref>\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[File:Wyberts Castle, site of - geograph.org.uk - 265817.jpg|thumb|left|160px|Site of Wyberts Castle]]\nThe parish church is a Grade I [[listed building]] dedicated to Saint Leodegar and dating from the late 12th century, although it was rebuilt around 1420. The [[chancel]] was rebuilt in 1760 and the church was restored by [[George Gilbert Scott Junior]] about 1880. The original church had a crossing tower which collapsed in 1419. The [[baptismal font|font]] is 15th century and there is a charity board in the north aisle dated 1794. In the north aisle there is a 14th-century black [[marble]] slab to Adam of Frampton and his wife. Records in the [[Court of Chancery|Chancery Court]] refer to proceedings between 1426 and 1432 where Roger Derrys, a London mason, was suing for payment following the rebuilding of Church [[Steeple (architecture)|tower]] and [[nave]]. The [[chancel]] rebuilding was carried out at the same time as the refronting of the Rectory, now Wyberton Park, by the Rector Dr John Shaw.<ref>{{NHLE|desc=St Leodegar|num=1147881|accessdate=30 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nWyberton Park, the tiled-roof red brick Grade II* listed former rectory {{convert|100|yd|m|sigfig=1}} to the south of the church, was built in 1689 by the incumbent, to replace a mud and stud rectory with one containing a \"kitchen, parlour, large staircase rising from the entrance door, two chambers, a large study and small closets on the second storey and garrets, and a large porch with steps ascending to it at the entrance.\" This improved rectory is seen by historian T. W. Beastall as indicating growing prosperity through increased acreage for crops and [[Animal husbandry|husbandry]] precipitated by fen drainage during the [[British Agricultural Revolution|Agricultural Revolution]].<ref name=Beastall>Beastall T.W. (1978), ''The Agricultural Revolution in Lincolnshire'', (History of Lincolnshire, volume 8), History of Lincolnshire Committee for the Society for Lincolnshire History and Archaeology, p.8. {{ISBN|0902668072}}</ref> The present house is a further 1761 part rebuild.<ref>{{NHLE|num= 1062042|desc=Wyberton Park, Church Lane, Wyberton|accessdate= 9 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nWyberts Castle is a [[scheduled monument|scheduled]] medieval moated site located at the south end of Wybert Lane, about {{convert|1|mi|km|1}} east of Wyberton. Excavations undertaken in 1959-1960 revealed remains of stone structures on the eastern half of the island, associated with pottery which suggested that the moated site was occupied during the 12th and 13th centuries and possibly until the 15th century. In the 18th century it was known as 'Wells Slade', suggesting that it was held by the Wells family who had a manor in Wyberton in the 14th century. The name 'Wybert's Castle' is thought to be of late 19th-century origin.<ref>{{NHLE|desc=Wyberts Castle|num=1018583|accessdate=30 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe village [[public house]] is the Pincushion Inn on London Road to the south of the village.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%; width:70%; border:0; text-align:center; line-height:120%;\"\n! colspan=\"12\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;\"|Population of Wyberton [[Civil Parish]]\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#9cc; color:navy; height:17px;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1801\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1811\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1821\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1831\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1841\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1851\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1881\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1891\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1901\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1911\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1921\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1931\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1951\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1961\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 2001\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 2011\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!  style=\"background:#9cc; color:navy; height:17px;\"| Population<ref>{{cite web|title=Vision of Britain|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/data_theme_page.jsp?u_id=10463907&c_id=10001043&data_theme=T_POP|accessdate=30 August 2011}}</ref>\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 477\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 353\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 487\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 530\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 584\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 647\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 646\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 659\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 627\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 653\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 664\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 829\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 1,809\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 2,889\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 3,790\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 3,747\n|}\n\n{{Geographic location\n|title = '''Destinations from Wyberton'''\n|Northwest = [[Brothertoft]], [[Langrick]], [[Coningsby]]\n|North     = [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]], [[Frithville]], [[Sibsey]]\n|Northeast = [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]], [[benington, Lincolnshire|Benington]], [[Skegness]]\n|West      = [[Kirton Holme]], [[Swineshead, Lincolnshire|Swineshead]], [[Helpringham]]\n|Centre    = Wyberton\n|East      = [[Freiston Shore]]\n|Southwest = [[Bicker, Lincolnshire|Bicker]], [[Algarkirk]], [[Spalding, Lincolnshire|Spalding]]\n|South     = [[Kirton, Lincolnshire|Kirton]], [[Fosdyke]], [[Holbeach, Lincolnshire|Holbeach]]\n|Southeast = [[Frampton, Lincolnshire|Frampton]], [[Skeldyke]]\n}}\n\n==Notable former inhabitants==<!-- This section is linked from [[London Borough of Lewisham]] -->\n*[[William Webster (builder)|William Webster]] &ndash; Builder - associated with a number of Thames embankments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icevirtuallibrary.com/doi/abs/10.1680/imotp.1888.20967|title=OBITUARY. WILLIAM WEBSTER, 1819-1888.|publisher=Institution of Civil Engineers}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Wyberton}}\n* [http://www.lincolnshire.gov.uk/windmills/section.asp?catId=3331 Former Wyberton Mill]\n* [http://www.wyberton.com Village web site (in construction)]\n* [http://www.boston.gov.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=850&Itemid=3497 Parish council]\n* [http://www.roffe.freeserve.co.uk/earthworks/moats/wyberton.htm Wybert's Castle]\n\n{{Portal bar|England|United Kingdom}}\n{{Lincolnshire|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Borough of Boston]]\n", "name_user": "Uziel302", "label": "safe", "comment": "Margart-> added template -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wyberton"}
